g.text: Kim Kitsuragi: "Another radiocomputer..." says the lieutenant, watching you circle around the machine. "Just sitting here without anyone in sight."
Reaction Speed: What he means is that these things cost *money*. Why would anyone just leave it behind?
Interfacing: This is the Rehm Civic radiocomputer, model RC5120, equipped with a Feld mainframe and a Rehm-compatible printer.
You: Yeah, how bad could it be?
East-Insulindian Repeater Station: "Good morning, Fortress Accident on Rue de Saint-Ghislaine, this is East-Insulindian Repeater Station 1."
Empathy: Doesn't it get lonely, sitting there all by herself?
You: "Doesn't it get lonely, doing this job?"
East-Insulindian Repeater Station: "Lonely?" For the first time you hear her chuckle through the rustle of static. "Why would it get lonely, I get to talk to people all day."
East-Insulindian Repeater Station: "Yes. Is that the production schedule?"
East-Insulindian Repeater Station: The old lady sighs, as a wave of static distorts her voice to a robotic sprawl. "If you are unsure, could you please take a look?"
Interfacing: The filaments you have would fit perfectly inside the compartment.

Mainframe: Four months later by an unknown author: "I am the only one left and it's gotten rather damp here. A few other businesses have gone under too. Slipstream switched to making skis and the hairdressers just left, cursing Martinaise. They're right, though, something's seriously wrong with this place. Martinaise, all of it."
Mainframe: So many. At last count there were approximately 10,000 heads for 10,000 headless men, all of which could be endlessly recombined.
Half Light: Is the lieutenant a little... scared? Just now when he looked around.
Interfacing: This is a *human interface* -- a retired person sitting behind a switchboard somewhere.
Logic: Password. Of course it would have a password. That's why there's a human administrator involved.
Suggestion: You should ask her for a hint.
You: "Why did you call me Fortress Accident?"
Reaction Speed: Saint-Brune 1147? That's what the street sign next to the church said...
Mainframe: This appears to be some kind of machine with a cube-shaped heart and a wired framework. The keyboard has a rectangular ON/OFF button; a piece of paper still hangs from the printer.
Mainframe: With a quiet determination the printer starts printing, a piece of paper unfolding like a hand-held fan. A black criss-cross of letters covers its surface.
You: It didn't need so many concept artists?

Mainframe: No, definitely not. A few more producers could have come handy though -- especially when dealing with writers, some of whom routinely skipped work because of 'mental health issues' and extremely unprofessional sleep schedules...
Mainframe: The speaker comes to life, static seeps through the machine's planar magnetic driver. An old lady greets you, her voice sounds a hundred years old...
Interfacing: The filament you have would fit perfectly inside the compartment.
You: I don't really care. (Look at the table of contents again.)
Kim Kitsuragi: "This is where the memory should go," the lieutenant notes, observing the machine.
Mainframe: The world had never seen their kind before and might never again.
Mainframe: At the eleventh hour, the lead designer, Zsiemsk-born Sulisław Zawisza, decided that what 'Wirrâl Untethered' needed was a secret mystical location at the extreme edge of the map...

Mainframe: This place was to be the *Valley of the Heads* -- where the heads of all the *headless* constructs could be found. The player would have been able to choose a head for their headless party member, and each head would been voiced on-air by a professional actor.
You: How many heads were there?
Kim Kitsuragi: The lieutenant taps his foot impatiently, his arms folded tight against his chest.
Interfacing: What if you broke the radiocomputer? What if it's never going to stop?!
Kim Kitsuragi: "It's your call." He looks over his shoulder, then back at the machine. "You're in charge of this expedition, officer."
Mainframe: The static gets louder, slowly filling up the abandoned hall. Until a voice speaks out, crackling and old, cutting into the air...
East-Insulindian Repeater Station: "Good evening, Fortress Accident on Rue de Saint-Ghislaine, this is East-Insulindian Repeater Station 1."
East-Insulindian Repeater Station: "Good afternoon, Fortress Accident on Rue de Saint-Ghislaine, this is East-Insulindian Repeater Station 1."

Shivers: On an island on the River Esperance, a small woman, all skin and bones, sits in a room filled with audio equipment. Thousands of tiny lights are reflected back from her prescription lenses, like stars in the dark.
Half Light: That sounds bad -- a log-in *attempt*. Something a criminal would do.
Logic: Don't worry. Passwords have a way of *turning up* sooner or later.
You: It's not very convincing, is it?
Mainframe: Her former colleagues would agree with you.
Mainframe: The dusty radiocomputer sleeps on its wired frame, forgotten and unused. Its keyboard has a rectangular ON/OFF button; a piece of paper still hangs from the printer.
Logic: This must be the information Soona is looking for -- she knows how to make sense of it.
Electrochemistry: But on the other hand, their obligations *were* piling up at an inhuman rate -- a rate that could only be amended by Pyrholidon.
Jump to: [Mainframe: "Tiles on the cube are still smoulde..."]
Mainframe: Tiles on the cube are still smouldering, casting the framework in a soft glow. Virescent PLAY and PRINT keys shine on the keyboard.
Interfacing: Something's missing -- there's no tape in the player.
Mainframe: What is clear is that one day an unidentified numeric anomaly occurred on the East-Insulindian Lintel front, just as the 'Wirrâl Untethered' project was being compiled that day.
You: And the anomaly caused all the data to get lost in the air?
You: I didn't understand a word of that.
Kim Kitsuragi: "We have one of these down at the station, but I never really learned how to use it."
East-Insulindian Repeater Station: "Yes, I am alive. I am 74 years old and my name is Yvonne."

East-Insulindian Repeater Station: The voice recites: "I am contractually obliged to protect the privacy of the filament holder Fortress Accident. Without filing a warrant with Lintel, I cannot give you access to this filament."
You: "Do you have any other information about this company?"
East-Insulindian Repeater Station: "One moment..." You hear her flip through a catalogue, before she reads out with studious care:
You: Gosh, where did they get all this money?
Mainframe: Let's just say it was a *real adventure* for their Igaunijan investor.

Encyclopedia: Igaunija -- a god-forsaken (and tiny) territory in Graad that has not once, but twice wasted its independence on microfascism. The less said about Igaunija the better. Matter of fact, let's stop saying things about it right now and continue what we were doing.
Mainframe: The production schedule depicts their glorious descent into bankruptcy.
You: Because of the concept artists?
You: This must be the anomaly Soona mentioned in the church log.

Mainframe: On the nature of the data loss, there's ominously little information in the production log. It comes at the very end, where things get fuzzy and dark, where tables and numbers seem to vanish into an eerie nothingness, before their Igaunijan investor pulled the plug...
Esprit de Corps: On the other hand... it's not that I'm *not* interested in abandoned radiocomputers.
Empathy: That's why she does this.
Savoir Faire: Of course you should turn it on -- don't you want to know what's on the filament?!
Mainframe: Behind the hatch sits a cube-like crisscross of filaments, smouldering in the dark like fireflies. Silver tape on the side says in a black marker: "THE OFF-SITE COPY".
Mainframe: It's empty like a beehive without its brood. Some cables have been left dangling, disconnected...
Mainframe: One of them even managed to steal some valuable company property before skipping town for good.
Mainframe: It was impossible not to fail. The project was too large and no amount of money could satiate the ever-expanding ambitions of the development team.
Encyclopedia: A hint system is not part of the protocol for repeater stations.
Mainframe: Do you really want to know? There seems to be a calculation here, but it may take a while...
Mainframe: Good call. It's more than the number of atoms in the observable universe.
You: That's pretty bad. So that's what did them in?
Mainframe: Always read the terms of service.
Logic: And let's face it, they didn't have any money left for a legal action.
Kim Kitsuragi: The lieutenant whispers into your ear: "She repeats passwords. Programming people are all... paranoid."
East-Insulindian Repeater Station: "Good, thank you." It's not clear whether she recognizes your voice. "Please repeat, how can I help you?"

Mainframe: "I didn't have a home anymore, so I started keeping it in the basement, in the ice bear refrigerator (near where I went to sleep). It was perfectly safe there, the temperature conditions were *optimal*."
You: Seems like a perfectly reasonable explanation.
You: Is there anything else from this lead programmer? (Proceed.)
Mainframe: That's not what her colleagues thought.
Mainframe: The production schedule ends with a few random notes that seem to be added sometime later.
Inland Empire: Marked by the devil itself!
Mainframe: It's blank. The lower edge of the paper has been torn off.
East-Insulindian Repeater Station: "Please repeat, is this the off-site copy?"
Interfacing: This is where the machine's memory should go.
Mainframe: A dusty radiocomputer sleeps on its wired frame, forgotten and unused. Its keyboard has a rectangular ON/OFF button; a piece of paper still hangs from the printer.
Mainframe: That is, until they discovered the Valley of the Heads.
You: What do you mean? I totally could have.
Kim Kitsuragi: "But we're looking for a fridge and we're pressed on time -- so..."
You: "Do you think I should turn it on?"
East-Insulindian Repeater Station: "As for me, well..." Some static. Then... "I am sitting in my cubicle surrounded by a wall of radios."
East-Insulindian Repeater Station: "The filament you have inserted into the reader."
You: "You mean that glowing thing I put inside?"
You: "Ah, right. Thanks for the explanation."

Kim Kitsuragi: "What, you're just going to guess?" The lieutenant shakes his head, staring at the glowing radiocomputer. Seems like the repeater station hasn't heard his words however, for the line is still silent.
East-Insulindian Repeater Station: "Good, thank you." It's not clear whether she recognizes your voice. "Please repeat, is this the off-site copy?"
You: Read about capital... I want to know about *money*.
East-Insulindian Repeater Station: The static drowns her response. "Any other questions?" you hear her ask when the connection finally improves.
Mainframe: Like a smooth drawer, the filament slides into place. On the keyboard, the PLAY key starts blinking.
Mainframe: Tiles on the cube are still smouldering, casting the framework in a soft glow. Virescent PLAY and PRINT keys shine on the keyboard.
Mainframe: Well, yeah. That, and the catastrophic data loss.
Mainframe: No, it was good. Too good.
Mainframe: It was the lead programmer's responsibility to oversee weekly maintenance of the off-site copy and, well, keep it off-site. An explanatory note from the lead programmer has been attached.
Half Light: Oh no... it was already glowing and now it's also making a *sound*? It's probably some alien Seolite technology...
East-Insulindian Repeater Station: "No, that's not it."
East-Insulindian Repeater Station: "'Fortress Accident SCA produces revolutionary interactive call-in radio games' -- that's what the catalogue says."
East-Insulindian Repeater Station: "Good, I've unlocked the production schedule. After ending the call, please press PRINT to access the filament."
East-Insulindian Repeater Station: Her answer is short and sharp: "No, that's not it."
Jump to: [East-Insulindian Repeater Station: ""Good. Please repeat the password.""]
East-Insulindian Repeater Station: "Good. Please repeat the password."
You: Read about the workforce... Who worked there, how long?
Mainframe: Fortress Accident employed 18 people, the bulk of the team composed of writers and concept artists. There were also radio programmers, sound engineers, a CEO, two marketing experts...
Mainframe: They thought they could bridge the gap with pure willpower and imagination.
Reaction Speed: You can always do it *after* the fridge.
Mainframe: Behind the hatch sits a cube-like crisscross of filaments, smouldering in the dark like fireflies. Silver tape on the side says in a black marker: "THE PRODUCTION SCHEDULE".
Mainframe: The paper is soaked with ink, its monochrome darkness spanning from margin to margin... It's not possible to make out any information.
Mainframe: ...and a single overburdened producer who developed a habit of popping Pyrholidon in the basement to escape his obligations.
You: "What happened? It's just covered in ink."
Mainframe: S. Luukanen-Kilde, the lead programmer of Fortress Accident: "The off-site copy was on-site because there was no *off-site* anymore, not for me, not after eight months of crunch."
You: How many combinations could you make out of that?
You: Wasn't there a copy of the game, a *backup*?
East-Insulindian Repeater Station: "Received. I will *register* this log-in attempt."
Conceptualization: Maybe it's the second part of the leitmotiv you saw on the stained glass window.
You: "Let's try the password for the production schedule."
Reaction Speed: Don't worry. Passwords have a way of *turning up* sooner or later.
East-Insulindian Repeater Station: "Please repeat -- is this the production schedule?"
Mainframe: It's a project report written by the lead producer Andrew 'Andy' Schott about 'Wirrâl Untethered', a radio game developed by studio Fortress Accident.
Electrochemistry: Four-hundred thousand reál?! Jommaijoo, these guys knew how to party!
You: Oh, so they were done in by their own ambition.
You: Read the notes at the end.
You: Tear off the printout and throw it away.
You: I could have bridged the gap.
Mainframe: Even then, success remained within an ever-narrowing margin of possibility that, despite everything, never entirely disappeared...
You: This is some insane shit. Who were these people?
You: Just let the numbers wash over you.
Kim Kitsuragi: "Maybe the body has *stopped* decomposing somehow..." He looks over his shoulder. "I don't know. You're in charge of this expedition, officer."
East-Insulindian Repeater Station: "Yes. Is that the off-site copy?"
East-Insulindian Repeater Station: "Received. I will *register* this log-in attempt."
East-Insulindian Repeater Station: "Good, thank you." It's not clear whether she recognizes your voice. "Please repeat, is this the production schedule?"
Jump to: [Mainframe: "Tiles on the cube are still smoulde..."]
Mainframe: The first tranche of seed financing brought in 150,000 reál, but then came the *delays*.
Kim Kitsuragi: "A radiocomputer..." says the lieutenant, watching you circle around the machine. "Just sitting here without anyone in sight." He sounds surprised and a bit cautious.
You: Okay, so that's what did them in?
Mainframe: In its short time of existence, Fortress Accident SCA managed to burn through truly *insane* amounts of money.
East-Insulindian Repeater Station: "Good, I've unlocked the off-site copy. After ending the call, please press PRINT to access the filament."
Kim Kitsuragi: "I'm afraid we're not doing that. Unless we want to wait for a month."
You: "I might have a password for the off-site copy."
You: "Yvonne, it's me again! How are you?"
Inland Empire: Have you stirred the ghost of the Doomed Commercial Area from its rest? Could this be its dismembered heart, beginning to flutter?
East-Insulindian Repeater Station: "Thank you and good bye," the old lady's voice disappears along with the static.
Jump to: [Mainframe: "Tiles on the cube are still smoulde..."]
Mainframe: The team spent weeks on the phone with Lintel, the service provider, but despite their diagnostics they could never produce a satisfactory explanation or pay for the loss.
Perception: It's just black upon black, nothing to see here.
East-Insulindian Repeater Station: "I work as a repeater at the East-Insulindian Repeater Station. It's my job to know where you are, Fortress Accident."
East-Insulindian Repeater Station: "Now please tell me the reason for your call, Fortress Accident."
Jump to: [East-Insulindian Repeater Station: ""Good. Please repeat the password.""]
Jump to: [Mainframe: "The first few pages give an overvie..."]
Mainframe: "I have compared the coordinates to a map of Revachol West. Turns out it's only 800 metres from here. The address is Saint-Brune 1147. I am going there to look this thing in the eye..."
Interfacing: She's right, actually -- nothing wrong with keeping this type of filament memory in a fridge.
Perception: A single speck of white shines out from the shade -- for some reason the printer decided to spare this one tiny dot of paper.
Mainframe: No, not the concept artists. It wasn't even the writers, with their panic attacks and three-hour lunches...
You: No, let's not go there.
You: What! They lost the whole game and wouldn't even pay for it?
Interfacing: Something's broken. Machines aren't supposed to behave like this.
Half Light: What does she mean *that's not it*?! What's the password then???
Mainframe: The first few pages give an overview of the capital and workforce, while the rest of it seems to be a production schedule.

Variable["doomed.moodboard_read_slogans"] == true and Variable["doomed.moodboard_read_calendar"] == true and Variable["doomed.moodboard_viewed_drawings"] == true and Variable["doomed.moodboard_viewed_photos"] == true and Variable["doomed.fireplace_have_read_it"] == true and Variable["doomed.doomed_radiocomputer_turned_on"] == true
East-Insulindian Repeater Station: "Now please tell me if there's anything else I can do, Fortress Accident."

Mainframe: The machine lights up like some prehistoric animal stirring from its slumber, revealing virescent PLAY and PRINT keys on the keyboard. The hatch on the machine's central compartment is wide open.

Radiocomputer: Variable["doomed.moodboard_read_slogans"] == true and Variable["doomed.moodboard_read_calendar"] == true and Variable["doomed.moodboard_viewed_drawings"] == true and Variable["doomed.moodboard_viewed_photos"] == true and Variable["doomed.fireplace_have_read_it"] == true and Variable["doomed.doomed_radiocomputer_turned_on"] == true
You: "Yvonne, my partner tells me that you're here because radiocomputer guys are all paranoid."
Mainframe: The first few pages give an overview of the capital and workforce, while the rest of it seems to be a production schedule.

Mainframe: "Still haven't gotten an answer from Lintel about what happened. All I could get were the physical coordinates of the error on the East-Insulindian front on that day. Since the computation happened on-air, I reckoned it had to coincide with an actually existing location..."
Jump to: [Mainframe: "Well, yeah. That, and the catastrop..."]
You: "Okay, but where are you? How did you know where I am?"
You: "This is the police. Please open this thing."
Half Light: Unbelievable!!! Who came up with those stupid passwords!
Mainframe: They tried to make a 4,000,000 reál game with 400,000 in their bank account.
You: Wait, why did a *radio game* need so many artists?

!(Variable["doomed.moodboard_read_slogans"] == true and Variable["doomed.moodboard_read_calendar"] == true and Variable["doomed.moodboard_viewed_drawings"] == true and Variable["doomed.moodboard_viewed_photos"] == true and Variable["doomed.fireplace_have_read_it"] == true and Variable["doomed.doomed_radiocomputer_turned_on"] == true)
East-Insulindian Repeater Station: "Yes, I am alive. I am 74 years old and my name is Yvonne. Now please repeat, is this the off-site copy?"
You: "I swear I haven't touched anything!"
You: "A password? I'm really bad at passwords. Can you give me a hint?"
Kim Kitsuragi: "Really? She just used the same password?" The lieutenant seems almost disappointed to discover that.
You: "And what's that -- this 'interactive call-in radio game'?"
Mainframe: Like a smooth drawer, the filament slides into place. On the keyboard, the PLAY key starts blinking.
Mainframe: Something spooky happened with the machines and the game was lost.
East-Insulindian Repeater Station: "Yes, I am alive. I am 74 years old and my name is Yvonne. Now please repeat, is this the production schedule?"
East-Insulindian Repeater Station: "That was a question. Have you inserted it into the core?"
You: Skim through the production schedule, whatever it is.
Mainframe: The filament slides out of its glowing nest.
Kim Kitsuragi: "Odd." The lieutenant runs his hand over the ink-soaked paper, staining his fingertips. "Something is obviously broken here."
Mainframe: No. Even then success remained within an ever-narrowing margin of possibility that, despite everything, never entirely disappeared...
Electrochemistry: He's dying for a cigarette. Come to think of it, you are, too.

East-Insulindian Repeater Station: "Open the hatch on the compartment. Don't touch the wires, a current is running through it, but the core is safe. There's a filament inside -- I need to know what it's called."
East-Insulindian Repeater Station: "They're merely cautious," says the old lady. "It's my job to protect their filaments as a password repeater at the East-Insulindian Station."
East-Insulindian Repeater Station: "Fortress Accident, is there anything else I can do for you today?"
East-Insulindian Repeater Station: "Fortress Accident is the company on whose name the terminal you're currently using has been registered to."
Physical Instrument: Looks like gibberish. Better get running again.
Mainframe: Mysteriously enough, it seems that the off-site copy happened to be *on-site* when the catastrophic data loss occurred...
East-Insulindian Repeater Station: "Now, can you please repeat the password?" the voice in the machine asks again. She sounds cold in the damp air.
Kim Kitsuragi: "Really? She just used the same password?" The lieutenant seems almost disappointed to discover that, as he murmurs: "Maybe those radiocomputer guys aren't that paranoid after all..."
Mainframe: Eventually the damage reached 400,000 reál with only half of the game finished.
You: Look at the table of contents.
Logic: Why did Fortress Accident have so many concept artists?
You: "What are you, a *machine*? Or are you *alive*?"
Mainframe: It sounds like something cracks, before the piece of paper starts filling up with pure black ink.
Mainframe: A bar of fabric right above the keyboard starts producing a soft hum. The sound of static seeps through the machine's planar magnetic driver.
Mainframe: When the project was returned, it was completely blank.
